05369nam a22009735i 9780823294657DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780823294657  a(DE-B1597)577371  a(OCoLC)1243057147  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a808.32231 aOhi, Kevin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInceptions :bLiterary Beginnings and Contingencies of Form /cKevin Ohi. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tExordium -- tPART I. POTENTIALITY AND GESTURE -- tPART II. NOVELS AND THE BEGINNINGS OF CHARACTER -- tPART III. OUR STONY ANCESTRY -- tPART IV. SOLITUDE AND QUEER ORIGINS -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe beginning is both internal and external to the text it initiates, and that noncoincidence points to the text’s vexed relation with its outside. Hence the nontrivial self-reflexivity of any textual beginning, which must bear witness to the self-grounding quality of the literary work— its inability either to comprise its inception or to externalize it in an authorizing exteriority. In a different but related way, the fact that they must begin renders our lives and our desires opaque to us; what Freud called “latency” marks not only sexuality but human thought with a self-division shaped by asynchronicity.From Henry James’s New York Edition prefaces to George Eliot’s epigraphs, from Ovid’s play with meter to Charles Dickens’s thematizing of the ex nihilo emergence of character, from Wallace Stevens’s abstract consideration of poetic origins to James Baldwin’s, Carson McCullers’s, and Eudora Welty’s descriptions of queer childhood, writers repeatedly confront the problem of inception. Inception introduces a fundamental contingency into texts and psyches alike: in the beginning, all could have been otherwise.For Kevin Ohi, the act of inception, and the potential it embodies, enables us to see making and unmaking coincide within the mechanism of creation. In this sense, Inceptions traces an ethics of reading, the possibility of perceiving, in the ostensibly finished forms of lives and texts, the potentiality inherent in their having started forth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aOpenings (Rhetoric). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aBaldwin, James.  aBeginnings.  aDefoe, Daniel.  aDickens, Charles.  aEliot, George.  aFriedrich, Su.  aJames, Henry.  aMcCullers, Carson.  aMilton, John.  aOppen, George.  aOvid.  aShakespeare, William.  aStevens, Wallace.  aWelty, Eudora.  aWordsworth, William.  abeginnings.  abirth.  acontingency.  aliterary form.  aorigins.  apotentiality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2021 Englishz978311075411708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2021z9783110753882oZDB-23-DSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073909140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329465740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823294657423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823294657/original  a978-3-11-073909-1  Fordham University Press Co